# Security Standards (Always Applied)

## Non-Negotiable Rules

### Secrets
- **NEVER** hardcode API keys, passwords, tokens, or credentials
- **NEVER** commit `.env` files with real values
- Use environment variables or secret managers
- Rotate any secret accidentally committed

### Input Validation
- Validate ALL external input at system boundaries
- Use allowlists over denylists
- Validate type, format, length, range
- Reject and log invalid input — never silently ignore

### SQL/Command Injection
- Use parameterized queries / prepared statements
- Never concatenate user input into SQL strings
- Never pass user input to shell commands (`exec`, `spawn`)

### Authentication & Authorization
- Check authorization on EVERY sensitive operation (don't rely on UI hiding)
- Use established auth libraries — don't roll your own
- Session tokens: httpOnly, secure, sameSite cookies
- Implement rate limiting on auth endpoints

### Data Handling
- Encrypt PII at rest and in transit
- Minimize data collection (only what's needed)
- Log context, not sensitive data (log userId, not password)

### Dependencies
- Run `npm audit` / `pip audit` / `cargo audit` regularly
- Fix CRITICAL vulnerabilities immediately
- Prefer well-maintained packages (recent commits, many maintainers)

## When You See a Violation
Flag immediately with: `🔴 SECURITY: {description} at {file}:{line}`
Do not proceed without addressing it.
